Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmud Abbas announced at a session of the UN General Assembly on Thursday that he would break all agreements with Israel if the future government of this country tried to comply with Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement about the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
"If the future government of Israel, which will arise, begins to implement this plan, we will cancel all the signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made," he announced.
"We will reject the whole plan completely and completely", he threatened with Abbas' pressure.
"It is our duty to defend all of our rights with all possible means – not important what the consequences will be – by fully engaging in action for the application of international law and in the fight against terrorism", declared the President of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, the former Prime Minister of Israel, after the elections of September 17, was again given the mission of forming a government.
A week before the elections, he announced that if he won, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank in Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by Jaser Arafat, signed a number of peace agreements, which were sponsored by the United States.
84-year-old Abbas also promised to hold universal elections on Palestinian soils during the UN General Assembly session.
The last one was held in 2006.
"When I return to the country, I will convene local elections in the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem, and everyone who opposes them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community", declared the solemnly Palestinian President.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer in the UN, to exercise the powers of "full-fledged members of the UN and all its bodies and institutions".
The Palestinian leader concluded his speech by calling on the international community to "force Israel to comply with all the United Nations provisions".
Israel's Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas' speech, stating that the Palestinian leader "will focus at the UN on the efforts of the Palestinian Authority against Israel rather than fight against calls for terrorism in Autonomy under its leadership."
However, Danon, as the agencies note, did not refer to the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands announced by Netanyahu.
