105 million PLN for video games companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Nearly PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the 3rd edition of GameINN on Friday.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by the NCBR was the development of a platform for the creation of field games based on an AR game engine that creates a real-world map with an application that allows users to transmit data; a test and training platform for the verification of practical skills at work and professional improvement using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of actual production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on virtual world interaction with the real-world concept of Industry 4.0 – reported in the NCBR release sent on Friday PAP.
The aim of the GameINN Sector Programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry in the global market in the perspective of 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game industry is already growing at 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 is 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared research agenda of GameINN and already reaching PLN 300 million support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral programme provide an important boost for the further dynamic growth of Polish gamedev", reads the release.
The video game industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The government's incentives for entrepreneurs to focus on innovation, such as R & D incentives, competence improvement programmes, IP box and support programmes implemented by the NCBR drive innovation activities of companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market", says Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The head of the Ministry of Science notes that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project funding, but also stays in their pockets – three quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R & D relief in 2018 than a year before.
"The amount of the deducted costs for R & D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in more than PLN 300 million savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in the three editions of GameINN", emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of NCBR Dr. Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that 78 innovative projects were awarded in two previous grant competitions with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million.
The huge interest in the 3rd competition and the variety of applications submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"It particularly welcomes the fact that the selected projects – as in previous editions – include projects concerning solutions not only for entertainment but also related to industry 4.0", he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and scientific units could apply for funding up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects received almost PLN 105 million of funding.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available on ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN Sectoral Programme is implemented under the Operational Programme Intelligent Development.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
