Majorca counts losses after the bankruptcy of the travel agency Thomas Cook
Over 25,000 foreign tourists will not come to Majorca in October as a result of the bankruptcy announced on Monday by the travel agency Thomas Cook.
On Friday, Marc Pons, a representative of the Autonomous Government of the Balearic Islands, announced that among the 25 thousand holiday makers who would not be able to take their leave in Majorca on October, there are also people who were to travel with companies indirectly associated with Thomas Cook, e.g. Neckermann.
Pons explained that 80 percent of expected holidaymakers who had to give up their vacation in Majorca due to the bankruptcy of a British company next month are German citizens and Scandinavian countries.
However, according to Pons, since Thomas Cook did not direct tourists to the Balearic Island in November-April, the losses to the local economy will be smaller.
He revealed that the Balearic Government had already started negotiations with international operators on "entering the Majorca market" following the bankruptcy of the British operator.
According to the estimates of the newspaper "Diario de Mallorca", in October over 1000 people will lose their jobs due to the tourist crisis in Majorca.
About 800 are fired employees of the Thomas Cook office in Palma.
Other people will lose their jobs mainly in the hotel sector.
On Monday, with the bankruptcy announcement by Thomas Cook in many Majorca hotels, the property owners demanded that guests pay an additional accommodation fee.
This situation was experienced, among others, by dozens of tourists from Poland.
The Balearic Government estimates that by Thursday, several dozen hotels in Majorca had ceased operations until at least the end of October in connection with the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook and its cooperating companies.
On the other hand, the Friday daily Diario de Ibiza indicates that the majority of Ibiza hotels that have cooperated with the Thomas Cook group do not intend to close out in the coming weeks.
The newspaper reminds us that on this balearic island, a British bankrupt was co-operating with 42 hotels.
On Wednesday, the autonomous Balearic authorities announced that they would ask the Spanish Government to support the region with EUR 100 million to cover losses caused by the bankruptcy of the travel agency Thomas Cook.
They revealed that the largest number of tourists affected in this archipelago, about 36,000 people, is located in Majorca.
According to the Balearic Government data, Thomas Cook owes local tourism companies, mainly hotel operators, for the implementation of agreements for the period July-September 2019 around EUR 5 million.
