Barbie against stereotypes.
Gender dolls
Barbie manufacturer has launched a series of sexually neutral dolls.
That's how he wants to fight stereotypes.
Barbie manufacturer has launched a series of sexually neutral dolls
Next to Barbie with different skin colors, figures or hairstyles, Mattel introduced a gender-neutral doll to the market.
"Creatable World" toys wear wigs.
Children can therefore decide whether their Barbie has short hair or long hair.
Their wardrobe consists of both trousers and dresses.
In the blink of an eye, dolls can become boys with girls and vice versa.
They are also available in different skin colors and with different clothes.
The emphasis on sexual characteristics was also abandoned – gender dolls no longer have full lips, long eyelashes and a thin waist or, in the case of Ken, wide arms.
The company believes that children do not like their dolls to have imposed sexual standards, and some parents and feminists are convinced that toys made for a particular gender inhibit the ambitions of girls and strengthen traditional stereotypes.
"New dolls will allow all children to feel free," says Mattel.
Barbie's doll, which appeared on the market in 1959 in a bathing suit and high-heeled shoes, has been criticised many times in the past for promoting "unhealthy women's stereotypes", such as the unnatural proportion of the body.
The company responded to criticism and has already introduced dolls of different skin colors, as well as more rounded shapes.
There were also dolls in hijab.
