Dakar: The largest mosque in West Africa was opened
Tens of thousands of people from all over Senegal gathered in the capital on Friday for the inauguration of a huge mosque, considered the largest in West Africa.
Muslims came by bus, car and foot to Bopp, where there was a new mosque, which could accommodate 30,000 believers.
The facility was built by the Mouride fraternity, belonging to the Sufi Islamic movement, which dominates Senegal.
Work on the mosque began ten years ago in a wet area of six hectares, which was handed over by the government.
The name of the mosque Massalikul Jinan (the Paths to Paradise) comes from the poem of Sheik Ahmadou Bamba Mbacke, the 19th century founder of the brotherhood, worshiped by the followers as a saint.
The mosque has five minarets.
The tall man is 78 meters tall.
The mosque in the middle holds 15,000 believers, and the other one can be on the outside stage.
In the richly finished interiors you can admire the gilded dome, gigantic chandeliers and hand-made decorations by Moroccan workers.
The builders claim that the mosque is the largest in West Africa, but there is no comparison between the mosques in other regions.
In Morocco, the Hassan II mosque in Casablanca can accommodate 105,000 believers.
The construction of the mosque, which cost more than EUR 30 million, was financed by private donations.
In addition to the land, the government has provided lighting, sanitary facilities and financed road works worth EUR 10.5 million.
