These trees can completely disappear from Europe.
"42 percent of the species of trees forming the state of Europe are at risk", warns the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in the "Red Book of European Trees" published on Friday.
The list is headed by chestnuts and raspberries.
IUCN, an organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was drawn up by experts who, on the basis of research, concluded that of the 454 species of trees present in Europe (and also elsewhere in the world), 42% are "highly threatened".
Among the causes of this is the rapid expansion of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
In terms of typical European stands, according to IUCN specialists 58 percent of species are threatened and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are threatened with extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Paper lists errors in the exploitation of the stands, accelerated urbanisation, too intensive logging, and subsequent forest fires and changes in the European ecostism.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also severely threatened.
"The consequences of human activity lead to the gradual disappearance of species of European plants and create the risk of the extinction of important and underrated varieties in Europe, which form the basis of European ecosystems and have an impact on the health of our planet", concluded Luc Bas, who heads the European IUCN office.
