Central Statistical Office: Poland is living better and better
According to a report on household budgets published by the Central Statistical Office on Friday, 44 percent of them were assessed as good or rather good in their material situation in the last year.
The year before was 37.2%, in 2016, 33.5%, and in 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of the situation of households, it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and more than 20% in 2009.
The material situation of self-employed households is best.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the other pole there are pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The subjective assessment of the material situation of households is also influenced by the number of children.
The worst is single parenting, of which 32 percent declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among non-childless households is 48.8%.
The effect of the 500+ programme is clearly visible in these statistics.
Before it was launched (in 2016) the worst material situation was assessed by single parents and multi-child families (with at least three children).
The improvement of subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of a rapid increase in income, mainly from work.
However, that is not all, because the percentage of households who consider their situation to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, there is no clear link at the level of voivodships between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are formulated by inhabitants of the Opole province, where 48.9 percent of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
There are further Lubuskie voivodships (47.7%), Śląskie (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and Zachodniopomorskie (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opole, disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94% of the national average in last year and 98% in Lubusek.
The highest income was obtained by residents of Mazowiecki (120 percent of the national average) and Silesia (104%).
On average, in Poland, the disposable income per person amounted to PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price changes) increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Against the background of previous years, this is quite a low result.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7% and a year later by 6.3%.
Although income growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187 in the last year, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased in real terms by 1.9% and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80% and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
