"Rzeczpospolita": To ignore a police officer's orders will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregarding a specific conduct order issued by a police officer is to be a new type of offence, punishable by fines, arrests, or restrictions on freedom.
The police unionists want to make this change.
The idea went to the Parliamentary Committee on Petitions.
"The case is serious, because already every year more than half a million misdemeanor cases are sent to Polish courts", we read.
"Rzeczpospolita" established that the petition, which the Independent Police Association writes to Members on the amendment of the Code of Offences, has a chance to succeed.
The petitioners propose a new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Offence.
It would read: "Whoever does not submit to the demand or order of a public officer, issued within the limits and under the provisions of the law, shall be subject to imprisonment, fine or restriction of freedom".
"Par. 3 of this provision speaks of an identical penalty for those who do not follow orders, prevent or impede the performance of a business activity", states the journal.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski said "Rzeczpospolita", that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal, he fears that if it is implemented, it can be used in political matters of manifestation.
"In situations of freedom demonstrations it would be unfavourable and instead of mitigating the situation, it would even exacerbate it", he adds.
The statistics provided by the newspaper show that 86% of citizens positively evaluated police interventions in 2018 and that every month the services take 1.5 million interventions in the city.
Buras is worried about Europe
Jáchym Topol's writing is in his blood.
His ancestors include editors, translators, writers.
The father, Josef Topol, was one of the most important postwar Czech playwrights, today mentioned in one row with Václav Havel.
Thus, Jáchym was under the curse of talent that he was trying to use from the beginning.
After eight years, he came back with "The Sensitive Man."
The heroes are Buras and Soňa together with two sons, who, however, do not form a typical Czech family.
They're wandering actors, traveling around Europe.
He's Shakespeare's lover and thief, she's a one-eyed translator who doesn't part with a bottle of wine.
One of the boys did not make a sound from birth, and for the other time stopped in infant times.
But it's not the heroes that's the most important thing in this story.
They are all just backgrounds for observing a world in which there is no longer room for artistic nomads.
It's a world of flealand, a society of old, suspicious people and promiscuous youth.
"Susceptible man" turns into an absurd play in some places.
Narration mimics didaskalia, and the talk of heroes creates this world.
The stage is a Europe full of concerns about its future, but also constant questions about the past.
Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has fallen, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is functioning.
However, the company has problems.
According to VRT, Brussels Airlines announced that they would cancel 105 flights in October due to problems with the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also fired 75 employees.
All trips with an office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The Ghent court also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian daughter companies, Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently around 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased at Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were supposed to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, spokesperson Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said that the company is now "fully operational" despite the bankruptcy of the British company's mother, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office then calmed down that the customers who bought the trips in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agents in the world – declared bankruptcy on Sunday night on Monday.
The immediate cause of bankruptcy was the collapse of the last chance talks on Sunday with creditors and potential investors.
The creditors demanded that, in addition to the £900 million rescue plan already agreed on in August, the company would obtain an additional €200 million as a guarantee for the winter period, when travel agents usually had a lower turnover.
However, the company's problems have been growing for several years, resulting in a debt of £1.6 billion.
