Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an unusual offer has been prepared for German visitors Görlitz.
Actions are intended to help fight the steady decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Görlitz is the easternmost town in Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, as the Guardian writes, the city is facing significant problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city also suffers from a steady loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which translated into a decrease in the population of the city by 25%.
In 2013, it amounted to 54 000 people.
To fight the depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been submitted to the program.
Two thirds of them were made up of the inhabitants of large cities.
The programme was also attended by people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
"When we applied, we thought the program was supposed to convince people to move to Görlitz," said one of the project participants.
"Now we feel it doesn't matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand free apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the average in the whole country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main objective of the programme is to get the opinion of the programme participants.
The information collected from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move – about what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild, responsible for the program.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to attract new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a programme to pay promising young professionals for living and working in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela, Italy, or in the American Tulsa, Oklahoma.
